### File Descriptions
- **app.py**  
  The main backend Python application file. It handles routing, data reading/writing from/to local text files in the `data/` directory, and serves the HTML templates. Since the application is not very complex, all backend logic (including data management, filtering, and page rendering) will be contained here.

- **templates/**  
  Directory containing all HTML template files for the web pages, each corresponding to one of the nine pages specified in the requirements. These templates will use a templating engine (e.g., Jinja2 if using Flask) to dynamically render data.

  - `dashboard.html` — Dashboard page layout and elements.
  - `membership_plans.html` — Membership plans listing with filter and navigation.
  - `plan_details.html` — Detailed view of a selected membership plan.
  - `class_schedule.html` — Class schedule with search and filter features.
  - `trainer_profiles.html` — List of trainers with search and filter.
  - `trainer_detail.html` — Detailed trainer profile page.
  - `pt_booking.html` — Personal training booking form.
  - `workout_records.html` — User workout history and progress tracking.
  - `log_workout.html` — Form to log a new workout.

- **static/**  
  Contains static assets such as CSS stylesheets, JavaScript files for client-side interactivity, and images (e.g., trainer photos, icons).

  - `css/styles.css` — Stylesheet for consistent styling across pages.
  - `js/scripts.js` — JavaScript for UI behaviors like button clicks, filtering, and navigation.
  - `images/` — Folder for storing images used in the app.

- **data/**  
  Stores all application data in text files as specified, used for reading and writing membership plans, classes, trainers, bookings, and workouts.

  - `memberships.txt` — Membership plans data.
  - `classes.txt` — Fitness classes data.
  - `trainers.txt` — Trainer profiles data.
  - `bookings.txt` — Personal training session bookings.
  - `workouts.txt` — User workout records.

This structure supports a clean separation of concerns, with a single backend file for simplicity, dedicated template files for each page, and organized static assets and data storage."

